1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,329
After a training session a few weeks ago, a young man came to see me and asked if he could talk with me for a few minutes.

2
00:00:07,680 --> 00:00:13,650
I knew that this young fellow, now about twenty-six, had been a very underprivileged child.

3
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:19,569
On top of this, he had experienced a mountain of misfortune in his early adult years.

4
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:25,250
I also knew that he was making a real effort to prepare himself for a solid future.

5
00:00:25,760 --> 00:00:36,049
Over coffee, we quickly worked out his technical problem, and our discussion turned to how people who have few physical possessions should look toward the future.

6
00:00:36,160 --> 00:00:39,569
His comments provide a straightforward, sound answer.

7
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:43,089
I've got less than $200 in the bank.

8
00:00:43,279 --> 00:00:48,529
My job as a rate clerk doesn't pay much, and it doesn't carry much responsibility.

9
00:00:48,799 --> 00:00:54,289
My car is four years old, and my wife and I live in a cramped second-floor apartment.

10
00:00:54,640 --> 00:01:00,930
But Professor, he continued, I'm determined not to let what I haven't got stop me.

11
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:05,890
That was an intriguing statement, so I urged him to explain.

12
00:01:06,400 --> 00:01:08,450
It's this way, he went on.

13
00:01:08,720 --> 00:01:12,609
I've been analyzing people a lot lately, and I've noticed this.

14
00:01:12,880 --> 00:01:16,849
People who don't have much look at themselves as they are now.

15
00:01:17,039 --> 00:01:18,289
That's all they see.

16
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:22,370
They don't see a future, they just see a miserable present.

17
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:24,690
My neighbor is a good example.

18
00:01:24,799 --> 00:01:30,930
He's continually complaining about having a low-pay job, the plumbing that's always getting fouled up,

19
00:01:31,039 --> 00:01:36,130
the lucky breaks somebody else just got, the doctor bills that are piling up.

20
00:01:36,320 --> 00:01:43,329
He reminds himself so often that he's poor that now he just assumes that he's always going to be poor.

21
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:49,809
He acts as if he were sentenced to living in that broken-down apartment all the rest of his life.

22
00:01:50,480 --> 00:01:55,650
My friend was really speaking from the heart, and after a moment's pause he added,

23
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,529
If I looked at myself strictly as I am, old car, low income,

24
00:02:00,560 --> 00:02:05,730
cheap apartment, and hamburger diet, I couldn't help but be discouraged.

25
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:10,130
I'd see a nobody, and I'd be a nobody for the rest of my life.

26
00:02:10,720 --> 00:02:16,690
I've made up my mind to look at myself as the person I'm going to be in a few short years.

27
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:20,529
I see myself not as a rate clerk, but as an executive.

28
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:22,770
I don't see a crummy apartment.

29
00:02:22,880 --> 00:02:25,250
I see a fine new suburban home.

30
00:02:25,360 --> 00:02:29,890
And when I look at myself that way, I feel bigger and think bigger.

31
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:34,529
And I've got plenty of personal experiences to prove it's paying off.

32
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:39,089
Isn't that a splendid plan for adding value to oneself?

33
00:02:39,279 --> 00:02:43,170
This young fellow is on the expressway to really fine living.

34
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:46,610
He's mastered this basic success principle.

35
00:02:46,799 --> 00:02:49,410
It isn't what one has that's important.

36
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:53,890
Rather, it's how much one is planning to get that counts.

37
00:02:54,400 --> 00:03:00,930
The price tag the world puts on us is just about identical to the one we put on ourselves.

